nship to political representation, and its increasing ubiquity have seen it transform in nuanced ways that demand explaining. Benjamin Moffitt contends that populism is not one entity, but a political style that is performed, embodied, and enacted across different political and cultural contexts. This new understanding makes sense of populism in a time when media pervades political life, a sense of crisis prevails, and populism has gone truly global.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDemocracy. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aPopulism. 4acrisis. 4ademocracy. 4aleadership. 4amedia. 4aperformance. 4apolitical style. 4apopulism. 4arepresentation. 4athe elite. 4athe people. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804799331zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799331423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799331.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles